<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-930-258  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 930 258.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 27 1989 v217 n23 pS48(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Radio over fiber? (Europeans considering phone links to domesticsubscribers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Purton, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Europeans are increasingly expecting radio, not fiber optics, willreplace copper wiring as the final connection to domesticservices.andP;  The cost of fiber optics has not fallen as fast asanticipated, while the boom in the mobile communications industryhas highlighted the demand for flexibility.andP;  Providers andcustomers agree that something needs to be done soon about thebottleneck in the final connection to the subscriber, or the localloop.andP;  Radio reception could greatly reduce the high cost ofcopper-wire maintenance.andP;  The European Commission is backing 23firms investigating a possible Pan-European communication systembased on pocket-sized transceivers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EuropeMobile communication systemsDemandFiber opticsCost of CommunicationsEuropean Community. Commission of the European Communities.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>